{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11837"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.89,0.03,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104105"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4438"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86424"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"658"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6463"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104105"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old male presents to the general practitioner due to sore throat and fever. The sore throat is significantly worse on the right side. His symptoms started three days ago and are getting progressively worse. This is accompanied with severe dysphagia and sialorrhoea. He has no relevant past medical history and he is up to date with his vaccinations. On examination, the patient looks unwell and he has a temperature of 38.4c. He has difficulty opening his mouth and his voice is muffled. ENT examination reveals soft palate swelling on the right side with extensive erythema and exudate. The uvula is deviated to the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epiglotitis","Peritonsillar abscess","Epstein-barr virus infection","Cervical adenitis","Sialadenitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a typical case of\u003Cstrong\u003E Peritonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E (Quinsy disease). Quinsy is the most common deep neck infection in adults and children. It is characterised with soft palate swelling due to the collection of pus between the palatine tonsil and the pharyngeal muscles subsequent to a bacterial infection. The most common causative organism is streptoccocus pyogenes and fusobacterium species. Quinsy typically presents with severe sore throat worse on the affected side, dysphagia and trismus. This is accompanied with infectious symptoms of fever and myalgia and can be associated with a \u0022hot potato voice\u0022.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of quinsy is typically made clinically without any further investigation. However culture swab can also be done to determine the causative organism. It is important to do a proper airway assessment in patients with suspected quinsy. Signs of airway compromise is an indication to an urgent referral and admission to the hospital. The mainstay treatment of quinsy is incision and drainage of the swelling, as well as antibiotics treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiglottitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis an important diagnosis to consider. Epiglottitis is a severe infection of the epiglottis which leads to airway compromise. It can present similarly to quinsy disease with severe sore throat, excessive drooling, trismus, and voice changes. However, the primary causative organism of epiglottitis is haemophillus influenzae type B (HiB), which makes the diagnosis much less likely in this case due to the patient\u0027s vaccination status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein Barr virus infection \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common viral infection in young adults. Patient with Epstein Barr virus infection commonly present with bilateral neck swelling due to lymphadenopathy, associated with infectious symptoms. It is unlikely for Epstein Barr virus infection to present with unilateral soft palate swelling. The toxic appearance of the patient, alongside with the ENT examination findings make quinsy disease more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical adenitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis inflammation of the cervical lymph nodes leading to lymphadenopathy. Patients with cervical adenitis present with palpable lymph nodes which is not the case in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialadenitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis an acute infection of the parotid gland. Patient commonly present with painful neck swelling on the submandibular region - where the parotid gland is located. It is unlikely for patient with sialadenitis to present with voice changes, trismus and dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Airway assessment should be done for all patients with suspected quinsy.","Quinsy disease present with severe unilateral sore throat, trismus, siallorhoea and infectious symptoms."],"references":["Therapeutic guidelines. Peritonsillar abscess (quinsy) and peritonsillar cellulitis. Ear, nose, and throat infections, Therapeutic gudelines. 2019. Accessed on 19 July 2022. Viewed at:  https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=peritonsillar-abscess-peritonsillar-cellulitis\u0026guidelinename=Antibiotic\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e47#toc_d1e47"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86424"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86424"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T12:47:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T12:47:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4438"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104105"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda